    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-05-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-05-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="908"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d908">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">715.16/27</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Honduran Minister</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">López Gutierrez</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation<note n="12" xml:id="d908fn12">File
                            translation revised.</note>]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-05-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 26, 1920</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: Amplifying the oral information I had the
                    honor to make known to the Department of State with respect to the ultimatum
                    recently served on the Government of Honduras by that of Salvador, I wish to say
                    to Your Excellency that I find the following telegram among my papers: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Tegucigalpa, May 12, 1920. The Minister of Honduras, Legation of
                            Honduras, Washington. Mondragón (Minister of Honduras in Salvador) says:
                            ‘President Meléndez awaits until four p.m. today dismissal Minister of
                            War Lagos, whom the Government of Salvador considers guilty of the
                            Araujo invasion, as being the only way to avert international war. That
                            the … (unintelligible) this evening for our border with war material …
                            (unintelligible)’ My Government declined to dismiss him.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>I take [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. Anto. Lopez G.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
